<h1 class="title">synthese</h1>
<div id="table-of-contents">
<h2>Table of Contents</h2>
<div id="text-table-of-contents">
<ul>
<li><a href="#sec-1">1. Crossing the Chasm</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-1" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-1"><span class="section-number-2">1</span> <i>Crossing the Chasm</i></h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-1">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Skipped:
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>"Whole product launches" p157-160
</li>
<li>"Launch the Invasion" p163-188
</li>
<li>"Getting beyond the chasm" p189-211
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li>The <a href="#ec46">Chasm</a> is a battle field that most start-up need to cross.  The war is so
intense that we model it using the <a href="#f3d9">D-Day</a> analogy.  Winning the war means
defining a <a href="#8163">positioning</a> making the <a href="#01cd">whole product</a> the only viable solution for
the customer in the target <a href="#dd57">market</a> segment. The unique beachhead target
<a href="#dd57">market</a> segment is choosen applying the <a href="#74c4">market development checklist</a> to a
collection of <a href="#1636">scenarios</a> built from <a href="#0526">informed intuitions</a>. Keep in mind that it
is way more difficult to cross the <a href="#ec46">Chasm</a> in a consumer <a href="#dd57">market</a> than a
business market.

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="ec46" name="ec46"></a> Chasm := in the <a href="#f558">Technology Adoption Life Cycle</a>, transition
from <a href="#a014">early market</a> to <a href="#194b">majority market</a> because their business conditions
are contradictory.  When <a href="#a014">early market</a> is saturated, there are no
customers for a while.  You become a target for competitions already in
the <a href="#194b">majority market</a> and a target for new entrants in the <a href="#a014">early market</a>.
Customers don't want you here as you disturb their conservative habits.
Expectations of investors are nevertheless present&#x2026; some use this
period to get control of startup tech.

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="dd57" name="dd57"></a> Market :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> set of actual and/or potential customers
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> for  given set of products
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> who have a common set of needs
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> and reference each other when making a buying decision
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="ce12" name="ce12"></a> Discountinuous Innovation := a product that needs the customer to
change its habits to acheive a task.
</li>

<li><a id="f558" name="f558"></a> Technology Adoption Life Cycle := <a href="img/technology-adoption-life-cycle.png">Tech Adoption Life Cycle</a>
each section represents a <a href="#47ad">phychographic profile</a> := [<a href="#c978">innovators</a>,
<a href="#7699">early adopters</a>, <a href="#8e70">early majority</a>, <a href="#ac74">late majority</a>, <a href="#9084">laggars</a>]

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="47ad" name="47ad"></a> phychographic profile := "combination of psychology and
demograhics that makes them ≠ from other groups"
</li>

<li><a id="c978" name="c978"></a> innovators := a few people&#x2026;
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="a961" name="a961"></a> &#x2026; with these business conditions :=
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> latest and greatest tech
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> no need to make huge profits out of them
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li>Willing to test tech in alpha stage + rank it against
competitors.  Only source of trust when marking a tech as
"good" or "bad" =&gt; advise "big bosses" about purchases
(<a href="#7699">early adopters</a>).
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="7699" name="7699"></a> early adopters :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>||early adopters|| &gt; ||innovators||, may have millions
dollars to invest.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="b918" name="b918"></a> Business conditions :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> buy a product vision&#x2026;
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> with a <a href="#ce12">discountinuous innovation</a> as its heart.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Adopting this product should bring high personal
recognition and rewards.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> First, they like a project: "going where no man has
gone" and going with them.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> The key of this relation is for the entrepreneur to
"productize" development of the tech as it goes: set a
serie of milestones defined as :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Accomplishable in mere mortal time
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> marketable product for the vendor
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Provide the customer with a ROI that can be
celebrated as a major step forward.
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="194b" name="194b"></a> majority <a href="#dd57">market</a> is where profits happens. It's composed of:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="8e70" name="8e70"></a> early majority := ||early majority|| &gt; ||early adopters||,
pursuing a product for pragmatic purposes.

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="de70" name="de70"></a> Business conditions:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> strong references (other early majority clients)
assuring that tech works&#x2026;
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> &#x2026; and will last.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> product must mean incremental, measurable and
predictable progress.
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="ac74" name="ac74"></a> late majority := ||late majority|| ~ ||early majority||

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Business conditions:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a href="#de70">early majority business conditions</a>
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> product has become a "standard" =&gt; profits
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="9084" name="9084"></a> laggars := not interesting.
</li>

<li><a id="a014" name="a014"></a> Early <a href="#dd57">market</a> := {innovators, early adopters}.

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Business condition :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a href="#a961">Innovator business conditions</a>
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a href="#b918">Early adopter business conditions</a>
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> False start if:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> the company sells the vision before it has a
product.  At best, the entrepreneurial compagny secures
a few pilot projects, but as schedules continue to slip,
the visionnary's position in the organization weakens
and support for the project is eventually withdrawn.

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Remedy: do one thing: turn pilot into product for the
customer and marketable object.
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Too much ambition, not enough money/skills/&#x2026;
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="f3d9" name="f3d9"></a> D-Day analogy :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>The model :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Products and companies ~ The allies
</li>

<li>Early market ~ England
</li>

<li>The english channel ~ The Chasm
</li>

<li>Strategic market segment in the mainstream ~ Beaches of Normandie
</li>

<li>Entrenched competitors ~ The axis
</li>

<li>Majority market ~ Eisenhower's Europe
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li>The key point is to focus an overabundance of support relatively to
a <a href="#dd57">market</a> that can be referenced by a broader
<a href="#dd57">market</a> in the <a href="#194b">majority market</a>.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> The more serious the problem you solve in this strategic nich
the faster you'll get out of the chasm: price the value of solving
this problem and rank it.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> This nich will let you access other ones: sum the money you can
make within each of them, this is how much you are supposed to make.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> For a platform, achieving critical density/mass is key for crossing
the Chasm: use a closed community and be the central agent of
it&#x2026; then extend.
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Applications are the domain of end users when platform are the
domain of IT.  IT is conservative, end users less and can force
the IT department to move. clothe the platform as an
application.
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="01cd" name="01cd"></a> Whole product := ∃ a ≠ between the value proposition made to
the customer and the ability of the shipped product to fulfill it.
product + additional services that fulfill this ≠ makes the whole
product.  <a href="img/whole-product.jpg">Whole product model</a>. The right side of the <a href="#ec46">Chasm</a> buy whole
product, the left one are ok with the basic product and happy with the
augmented product.  How much should we add to our product so that it
becomes a good enough whole product?  <a href="img/simplified-whole-product-model.jpg">simplified whole product model</a>.
To build it, start from the beachhead customer <a href="#1636">scenario</a> and be as
practical as possible.
</li>

<li><a id="0526" name="0526"></a> Informed intuition := isolate a consumer pattern like
"visionaries" or "pragmatists" and go for them.  This pattern should be
compelling enough that it just stick and people around you just grasp it
when heard.
</li>

<li><a id="1636" name="1636"></a> Scenario :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> One A4 page that make obvious the value of a product for a User:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Header:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>User: The entity that is could pay for a product.
</li>

<li>Technical buyer: Who is in charge in the User to evaluate if yes or
no a product spec match a need.
</li>

<li><a id="6a45" name="6a45"></a> Economic buyer: Who is in charge in the User to evaluate if yes or
no the price of a product to solve a technical need is worth
it.
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="ba35" name="ba35"></a> A day in the life, before:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Scene: Moment of frustration, what is the user about to attempt
?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Desired outcome: What is the user trying to accomplish? Why is
it important?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Attempted approach: without the new product, how does the user
go about the task?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Interfering factors: What, How and Why does it goes
wrong?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Economic consequences: So what? What is the impact of
the user failing to accomplish the task productively?
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> A day in the life, after: same as <a href="#ba35">before</a> except:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> New approach: with the product, how does the end user go
about the task?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Enabling factor: What is it about the new approach that
allows the user to get unstuck and be productive?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Economic rewards: what are the costs avoided or benefits
gained?
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li>Example: p96
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="74c4" name="74c4"></a> Market development checklist := To rank <a href="#1636">scenarios</a> against this
list of criterions, each from 1 to 5.  The first 4 criterions filter for
valid beachhead, others are "nice to have":

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Target customer: is there a single, identifiable, creditworthy,
accessible to sales channels, <a href="#6a45">economic buyer</a> for the <a href="#01cd">whole product</a>?
If you want to be a 10m$ company, aim at a 10m$ <a href="#dd57">market</a> because you
have to be the leader of it.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="d697" name="d697"></a> Compelling reason to buy: economic consequences wrt product
solution worthy to be implemented?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a href="#01cd">whole product</a>: can our company with the help of partners and
allies field a complete solution to the target <a href="#d697">compelling
reason to buy</a> in the next 3 months such that we can be in the
market by the end of next quarter and be dominating the market
within the 12 months thereafter?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Competition: "Never attack a fortified hill".  Has this problem
already been addressed by another company such that they have
crossed the <a href="#ec46">Chasm</a> ahead of us and occupied the space we would be
targeting?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Partners and allies: existing relationship with other companies
needed to fulfill the <a href="#01cd">whole product</a>?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Distribution: Do we have a sales channel in place that can call
on the target customer and fulfill the <a href="#01cd">whole product</a> requirements
put on distribution?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Pricing: Does price match the releive to fix the targetted pain?
The distribution of this money accross all actors is sufficiently
appealing?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Positionning: Is the company credible as a provider of products
and services to the target niches?
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Next target customer: Does this nich is a door to an other one?
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a id="8163" name="8163"></a> Positioning :=

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Pick a location in the <a href="img/competitive-positioning-compass.jpg">competitive positioning compass</a>.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="2026" name="2026"></a> Use the <a href="#49cc">market alternative</a> and the <a href="#45d6">product alternative</a>
so that the market can locate your company's unique value: a <a href="#3fd3">claim</a>,
an <a href="#2d40">evidence</a>, a communication (how to transmit <a href="#3fd3">claim</a>, and <a href="#2d40">evidence</a>),
feedback and adjustments (because competitors will launch
counter-measures).

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="49cc" name="49cc"></a> market alternative := company that the target
consumer has been buying for years.  The problem they address is
the one we address.  The budget they represent is the money we
are going to represent.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="45d6" name="45d6"></a> product alternative := competitor challenging the
<a href="#49cc">market alternative</a>.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="3fd3" name="3fd3"></a> claim := someone has to understand the claim in a
few sentences: the elevator pitch. For <i>beachhead target
customer segment</i>, who are dissatisfied with <i>the current <a href="#49cc">market
alternative</a></i> our product is a <i>new product category</i> that
provides <i>key problem-solving capability</i> unlike <i>product
alternative</i> we have assembled <i>key whole profuct features for
your specific application</i>
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> <a id="2d40" name="2d40"></a> evidence := <a href="img/positioning-evidence.jpg">positioning evidence</a>
</li>
</ul>
</li>

<li><a href="#8163">Positioning</a> is the single largest influence on the buying decision,
it exists in people's heads already not in your words and doesn't
like stuff to change.  It's goal is to make a product easier to
buy. It follows a couple of rules:

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Name it and frame it. Minimum for tech enthousiasts ex:
"middleware" (just a name) renamed to "enterprise application
integration" (name + frame).
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Who for and what for. Minimum for visionnaries.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Competition and differentiation.  Setup the context so that
pragmatist can evaluate how much to pay for what.
</li>

<li><code>[&#xa0;]</code> Financials and futures. Makes sure that the entity behind
the product is here to stay. Minimum for conservative.
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
